## Rules Registry

| Rule File | Scope | What It Enforces |
|-----------|-------|-----------------|
| `frontend.mdc` | `expense-tracking-frontend/**/*.{js,jsx,css}` | Folder structure, DRY, design patterns, Redux, build readiness |
| `backend.mdc` | `expense-tracking-backend/**/*.java` | SOLID, folder structure, DRY, Kafka, API standards, build readiness |
| `testing.mdc` | `**/*.test.*`, `**/test/**/*.java` | Jest + RTL, JUnit + Mockito, naming, coverage |
| `security.mdc` | Always | JWT, OWASP, input validation, CORS, error handling |
| `planning.mdc` | Always | Task decomposition, Plan Mode triggers, parallel strategy |
| `deployment.mdc` | Always | 12-factor compliance, Docker, CI/CD, env management, pre-deploy checks |

## Coordination Rules

- Agents never modify files outside their scope
- Frontend agent owns `expense-tracking-frontend/**` (except i18n files and test files)
- Backend agent owns `expense-tracking-backend/**` (except entity/model classes and test files)
- Database agent owns entity/model classes, migration scripts, and repository interfaces
- QA agent owns test files in both directories
- i18n & A11y agent owns `**/i18n/**` and `**/translations/**`
- DevOps agent owns `Dockerfile*`, `docker-compose*`, `Jenkinsfile`, `.env*`, `nginx.conf`
- Documentation agent owns `*.md` files and OpenAPI config
- Security, Reviewer, Debug, and Refactor agents are read-only analysts (propose changes, domain agents apply)
- When in doubt about ownership, the Orchestrator decides

## Rule Maintenance Protocol

Rules and agent definitions must stay in sync with the codebase. After completing significant code changes:

1. **Orchestrator** checks: did this change introduce a new pattern, folder, library, or convention?
2. If yes, the Orchestrator identifies which rule file(s) need updating
3. The relevant agent (Frontend/Backend/QA) proposes the rule update
4. The update is applied to `.cursor/rules/{rule}.mdc` or `.cursor/agents/{agent}.md`

### Triggers for Rule Updates

| Code Change | Rule to Update |
|-------------|---------------|
| New npm package added | `frontend.mdc` -- add to tech stack and usage patterns |
| New Maven dependency | `backend.mdc` -- add to tech stack or design patterns table |
| New feature folder created | `frontend.mdc` or `backend.mdc` -- verify folder structure section |
| New microservice module added | `backend.mdc` -- add to module structure |
| New Redux slice/feature | `frontend.mdc` -- verify state management section |
| New Kafka topic | `backend.mdc` -- verify messaging standards |
| New environment variable | `deployment.mdc` -- add to env var documentation |
| New Docker service | `deployment.mdc` -- update Docker standards |
| New design pattern introduced | `backend.mdc` or `frontend.mdc` -- add to design patterns table |
| New shared component created | `frontend.mdc` -- verify DRY section |
| New common-library class | `backend.mdc` -- verify DRY section |

### How to Update Rules

When updating a rule file:
- Keep the YAML frontmatter intact (description, globs, alwaysApply)
- Add the new pattern to the relevant section, not as a new section
- If a section exceeds 15 items, consider splitting it
- Include a concrete example (code snippet or file path) for new patterns
- Never remove existing rules unless the pattern is deprecated in the codebase
